text: It’s clear to all but @realDonaldTrump that it was he who forced the DACA issue when he ended the prgm. Dems have been willing to negotiate for months, & forged several bi-partisan deals, but his refusal to take yes for an answer led to his partisan plan that only got 39 votes.

I agree with @RonWyden: “Congress needs to get to the bottom of what has happened to our democracy. But we’ve been stonewalled, particularly when it comes to following the money.” #DefendOurDemocracy

With the budget deal signed & sealed, we have to keep our focus on the Russian interference in our elections, the investigation to get to the bottom of their meddling, & our work to #DefendOurDemocracy.

One of my biggest concerns for Puerto Rico has been the damaged power grid, which NYers from @ConEdison have been working to repair. Our bill will bring an addl $2 billion specifically for Puerto Rico & USVI to repair, improve, & strengthen their electric grids.

Working with @NydiaVelazquez & @RepJoseSerrano, our budget deal locked in over $89 Billion for recovery, repairs, & future mitigation to help infrastructure, schools & economic revitalization in communities impacted by disasters, including #PuertoRico & the USVI

After a decade of cuts to prgms that help the middle class, we now have a dramatic reversal. Funding for education, infrastructure, fighting drug abuse, & @NIH will all, for the first time in years, get very significant increases & keep us on track to support American families.

Our budget will also finally fund the opioid fight. @warsnotover, my #SOTU guest, is the mother of a veteran who became hooked on opioids in the depths of PTSD, who waited 16 mos for his 1st appointment at the VA but died from an overdose two wks before he could get treatment.

What does this budget really do? It provides billions to support for community health centers, child care, disaster relief, to rebuild & improve veterans hospitals & clinics, to lower prescription drug costs for seniors, to make college more affordable, & to fix infrastructure.
.@SenateDems have argued that we need to fund our military AND our middle class programs. I am proud to say our budget does both.

While @POTUS threatens shutdowns & stalemates, Congress has done the hard work of finding compromise & consensus. We have reached a budget deal that neither side loves but both sides can be proud of. That’s compromise. That’s governing. We should do more of it.

This budget deal also includes long-awaited disaster relief for TX, LA, FL, Puerto Rico & the USVI. This recovery aid could not come a moment too soon. @SenBillNelson worked so hard for both Florida & Puerto Rico relief, as did so many others in our caucus.
Very pleased to announce alongside @SenateMajLdr that we have reached a two-year budget deal that will benefit our country in so many ways.

Can you imagine the outrage on the right if President Obama’s message was being spread by WikiLeaks or Julian Assange or Kremlin sources?

The Republican campaign to attack the FBI has been joined by the same forces that interfered in the 2016 election – WikiLeaks, Julian Assange, and Russia. Just a few years ago those things were actually attacked by the GOP, particularly by the hard right. How things have changed.

The Republican Majority on the House Intelligence committee has manufactured a secret memo of partisan talking points, full of innuendo & glaring omissions, intended to suggest widespread corruption at the Dept. of Justice & the FBI.
The right has waged an aggressive & coordinated attack on the integrity of the Special Counsel, and now that political smear campaign has bled into a spiraling & delusional attack on the @FBI itself.

In 2016, @FBI was tasked with a mission of great importance to all Americans: investigating Russia’s interference in our elections. But ever since Special Counsel Mueller was appointed, the GOP & right-wing media have been desperate to distract the nation from his investigation.
Important to remember, in the midst of a govt shutdown, the GOP - which used to be considered the "law & order party"- continued their attack on our nation's top law enforcement agency, the @FBI.

We have been skating by on continuing resolution after continuing resolution for almost 6 months. First, we passed a 3-month CR, then a 2-wk CR, then a 1-month CR. Now we are offered another month-long delay of the inevitable. We can’t keep kicking the can down the road.
Democrats & Republicans have been negotiating for months across several issues. A bipartisan deal is within reach & now is the time to reach it. Now. Not a month from now.

What a disgrace. That's what this bill is. It's an absolute disgrace. There is no reason for a single middle-class family to pay more while every single corporation pays less.

Special Counsel’s investigation is an impt one for our democracy. We have to get to the bottom of what happened & find out how Russia was able to wage a successful info campaign to influence our election & to what extent it was in coordination w/ anyone from the Trump campaign.

President Trump’s appointed chairman of the @FCC, @AjitPaiFCC, is on the verge of eliminating #NetNeutrality – bringing to an end the free & open internet that has enabled so many successful companies & created so many jobs.

The nomination of Leonard Grasz is indicative of the new Republican playbook: if you don’t like the message, shoot the messenger. If you don’t like what the @ABAesq is saying about your judicial candidates, call it partisan – even if you praised its judgment just months ago.

.@SenateMajLdr once likened a well-qualified rating from @ABAesq to “getting straight A+’s on your report card.” Now the GOP is singing a much different tune as two of President Trump’s judicial nominations have received unanimously not-qualified ratings.

Leonard Grasz is just the third judicial nominee since 1989 to be unanimously deemed “not qualified” by the @ABAesq. A panel of nonpartisan, legal experts unanimously concluded that this man is not fit to be a judge. What else do my colleagues need to know?
This evening, the Senate will vote on whether or not we should consider the nomination of Leonard Grasz to be a judge on the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals.
